docs.abstract: Our tech columnist tried to skip digital news for a while. His old-school experiment led to three main conclusions.
docs.snippet: Our tech columnist tried to skip digital news for a while. His old-school experiment led to three main conclusions.
docs.lead_paragraph: I first got news of the school shooting in Parkland, Fla., via an alert on my watch. Even though I had turned off news notifications months ago, the biggest news still somehow finds a way to slip through.

headline.main: For Two Months, I Got My News From Print Newspapers. Here’s What I Learned.
headline.print_headline: Yesterday’s News Today: Deep, Informed, Accurate and Inky

docs.abstract: How two tech-industry news sites, The Information and Stratechery, may show a path forward.
docs.snippet: How two tech-industry news sites, The Information and Stratechery, may show a path forward.
docs.lead_paragraph: You could almost hear the trumpets blaring in the background of Mark Zuckerberg’s announcement last week that Facebook would now promote local news stories in its news feed.

headline.main: A Crazy Idea for Funding Local News: Charge People for It
headline.print_headline: How to Save Local News: Make People Pay for It

docs.abstract: The ride-hailing company is teaming up with Magna, a major auto supplier, to jointly develop self-driving car systems. It’s the latest in a series of alliances made by Lyft.
docs.snippet: The ride-hailing company is teaming up with Magna, a major auto supplier, to jointly develop self-driving car systems. It’s the latest in a series of alliances made by Lyft.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — The ride-hailing service Lyft has agreed to alliances with just about anyone working on driverless car technology. Its latest partnership aims to make its autonomous vehicle technology available to any car manufacturer.

headline.main: Lyft to Bring Driverless Car Tech to Broader Auto Industry
headline.print_headline: Lyft to Share Driverless Advances in Deal

docs.abstract: Known for its moneymaking consistency, Google’s parent company ran into the increased price of ensuring its search engine is featured on mobile devices.
docs.snippet: Known for its moneymaking consistency, Google’s parent company ran into the increased price of ensuring its search engine is featured on mobile devices.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Quarter after quarter, investors have become accustomed to Alphabet’s revenue and profit growing at a pace that seems to defy gravity for a company well past its start-up years.

headline.main: Alphabet’s Earnings Disappoint. Blame It on the iPhone.
headline.print_headline: Alphabet Posts Disappointing Earnings. Blame the iPhone’s Success.

docs.abstract: The video-sharing site said it took down more than eight million videos in the fourth quarter of 2017. The vast majority were flagged by computers.
docs.snippet: The video-sharing site said it took down more than eight million videos in the fourth quarter of 2017. The vast majority were flagged by computers.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — The vast majority of videos removed from YouTube toward the end of last year for violating the site’s content guidelines had first been detected by machines instead of humans, the Google-owned company said on Monday.

headline.main: YouTube Says Computers Are Catching Problem Videos
headline.print_headline: YouTube Says Computers Are Catching Video Pitfalls

docs.abstract: Next to Apple’s iOS and Google’s Android, Amazon’s voice assistant may be turning into the third great consumer computing platform of our era.
docs.snippet: Next to Apple’s iOS and Google’s Android, Amazon’s voice assistant may be turning into the third great consumer computing platform of our era.
docs.lead_paragraph: My wife and I were just settling into bed one night when Alexa, the other woman in my life, decided to make herself heard.

headline.main: Why We May Soon Be Living in Alexa’s World
headline.print_headline: Alexa Will Be Everywhere. We’d Better Get Used to It.

docs.abstract: In this week’s tech newsletter, a look at Netflix’s huge earnings, Democrats splitting with Silicon Valley and Apple’s new speaker.
docs.snippet: In this week’s tech newsletter, a look at Netflix’s huge earnings, Democrats splitting with Silicon Valley and Apple’s new speaker.
docs.lead_paragraph: Each Friday, Farhad Manjoo, technology columnist at The New York Times, reviews the week’s news, offering analysis and maybe a joke or two about the most important developments in the tech industry. Want this newsletter in your inbox? Sign up here.

headline.main: Farhad’s Week in Tech: Netflix Is a Monster, and Apple’s HomePod Arrives Soon
headline.print_headline: Netflix Is a Monster; Apple’s HomePod

docs.abstract: Uber’s chief, Dara Khosrowshahi, said the company had not stolen trade secrets from the self-driving car unit of Google’s parent company, but expressed “regret for the actions” that led to the suit.
docs.snippet: Uber’s chief, Dara Khosrowshahi, said the company had not stolen trade secrets from the self-driving car unit of Google’s parent company, but expressed “regret for the actions” that led to the suit.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Waymo and Uber settled their legal fight on Friday, nearly a year after Waymo first accused the ride-hailing company of plotting to steal important self-driving car technology.

headline.main: Uber and Waymo Settle Trade Secrets Suit Over Driverless Cars
headline.print_headline: In Settlement, Waymo Gets $245 Million in Uber Stock

docs.abstract: The long-awaited court fight over accusations that Uber conspired to steal plans for self-driving cars began in federal court.
docs.snippet: The long-awaited court fight over accusations that Uber conspired to steal plans for self-driving cars began in federal court.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — It is not often that a sports metaphor becomes the news of the day in a legal fight over intellectual property theft accusations between two tech industry titans.

headline.main: Waymo v. Uber Trial Opens With a Battle of Sports Metaphors
headline.print_headline: Cheater or Champion? Uber Swipes Back in Court

docs.abstract: Debbie Dooley, an early Tea Party organizer who backs President Trump, says embracing alternative energy is part of a consistent worldview.
docs.snippet: Debbie Dooley, an early Tea Party organizer who backs President Trump, says embracing alternative energy is part of a consistent worldview.
docs.lead_paragraph: LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga. — Debbie Dooley’s conservative profile seems impeccable. The gun-owning daughter of a Baptist preacher, she was an early organizer for the Tea Party movement. She voted for President Trump and still supports him.

headline.main: A Gun-Owning Trump Fan’s New Crusade: Clean Energy
headline.print_headline: Clean Energy Has Advocate On the Right
